# Xcode build / test ‚Äî only when asked

**Do not** run **`xcodebuild`** (`clean`, `build`, `build-for-testing`, or `test`) proactively after code changes, feature work, or bug fixes ‚Äî even when you added or updated tests.

## When to run

Run the Xcode workflow (**`.cursor/rules/xcode-run-test.mdc`**) only when:

1. **Explicit test / build request** ‚Äî the user asks to **run**, **launch**, **build**, **test**, **‚åòU**, verify compile, or similar. **Run on Dre's phone** uses **`.cursor/rules/xcode-run-dres-phone.mdc`** (clean ‚Üí rebuild ‚Üí install + launch).
2. **Commit and/or push** ‚Äî the user asks to **`git commit`**, **`git push`**, or ship / commit-and-push. **Before** staging or committing:
   - On **iPhone 17 simulator** (`platform=iOS Simulator,name=iPhone 17,OS=latest` per **`xcode-run-test.mdc`**): **`clean`** ‚Üí **`clean build-for-testing`** ‚Üí **`test`**.
   - Fix compile errors, **failing tests**, regressions you introduced, and **all project build warnings** (**`xcode-fix-build-warnings.mdc`**); repeat until green.
   - **Do not commit or push** until **BUILD SUCCEEDED**, **all tests pass**, and **project warning count is 0**.

## When not to run

- After implementing or fixing something, unless one of the triggers above applies.
- To ‚Äúverify‚Äù or ‚Äúconfirm‚Äù your own work at handoff ‚Äî tell the user the change is ready; they can ask to test.
- Because **`code-changes-require-tests.mdc`** asked you to **author** tests ‚Äî writing tests does **not** require executing **`xcodebuild`**.

## Handoff without a build

When finishing work without a test request, skip build logs and do not claim **BUILD SUCCEEDED** / **FAILED**.
